addition of \f(CW\*(C`assign\*(C'\fR, which adds new columns based on calculations from other columns
.PP
addition of \f(CW\*(C`hoa2aoh\*(C'\fR, transforming hash of arrays to array of hashes
.PP
addition of \f(CW\*(C`predict\*(C'\fR, using results from \f(CW\*(C`aov\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`glm\*(C'\fR, and \f(CW\*(C`lm\*(C'\fR
.PP
addition of \f(CW\*(C`aoh2hoh\*(C'\fR transforming array of hash into hash of hashes, \f(CW\*(C`intersection\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`uniq\*(C'\fR, and \f(CW\*(C`vals\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fR\f(CI\*(C`aov\*(C'\fR\fI\fR
.IX Subsection "aov"
.PP
Bug fixes
.IX Subsection "Bug fixes"
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fR\f(CB\*(C`size_t\*(C'\fR\fB underflow on empty arrays.\fR Three loops were bounded by \f(CWav_len(...)\fR
compared against an unsigned counter; \f(CW\*(C`av_len\*(C'\fR returns \f(CW\-1\fR for an empty array,
which turned \f(CW\*(C`k <= len\*(C'\fR into a \f(CW\*(C`SIZE_MAX\*(C'\fR loop. The \f(CWstack()\fR value loop, the \f(CW\*(C`.\*(C'\fR
column\-expansion loop, and the \f(CW\*(C`group_stats\*(C'\fR column loop now use a signed
\&\f(CW\*(C`SSize_t\*(C'\fR bound.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fBHoH row count.\fR Row count for hash\-of\-hashes input was taken from the return
value of \f(CW\*(C`hv_iterinit\*(C'\fR; it now uses \f(CWHvUSEDKEYS(hv)\fR with a separate
\&\f(CW\*(C`hv_iterinit\*(C'\fR, matching \f(CW\*(C`predict\*(C'\fR.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fBBuffer overflow in interaction parsing.\fR \f(CW\*(C`strcpy(right, colon + 1)\*(C'\fR into a
fixed \f(CW\*(C`char right[256]\*(C'\fR is now \f(CW\*(C`snprintf(right, sizeof(right), ...)\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Performance / memory
.IX Subsection "Performance / memory"
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fBRemoved the per\-row \fR\f(CB\*(C`row_x\*(C'\fR\fB scratch allocation.\fR Design rows are built
directly into \f(CW\*(C`X_mat[valid_n]\*(C'\fR; \f(CW\*(C`valid_n\*(C'\fR simply does not advance on a rejected
row. Interaction columns read their operands from the same in\-progress row, so
the logic is unchanged.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fR\f(CB\*(C`row_names\*(C'\fR\fB is no longer dead.\fR Surviving row names are transferred (pointer
move, no copy) into \f(CW\*(C`surv_names\*(C'\fR to key \f(CW\*(C`fitted.values\*(C'\fR; rejected rows are freed
in place.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fBDropped a \fR\f(CB\*(C`restrict\*(C'\fR\fB UB.\fR \f(CW\*(C`orig_data_sv\*(C'\fR aliases \f(CW\*(C`data_sv\*(C'\fR; the \f(CW\*(C`restrict\*(C'\fR
qualifier was removed.
.PP
New, \f(CW\*(C`predict\*(C'\fR\-compatible output keys
.IX Subsection "New, predict-compatible output keys"
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fR\f(CB\*(C`coefficients\*(C'\fR\fB\fR ŌĆö OLS estimates recovered by back\-substitution on the R factor
left in \f(CW\*(C`X_mat\*(C'\fR against Q\*(Aqy in \f(CW\*(C`Y\*(C'\fR (no re\-derivation). Keys are the expanded term
names (\f(CW\*(C`Intercept\*(C'\fR, continuous names, \f(CW\*(C`base.level\*(C'\fR dummies, and \f(CW\*(C`a:b\*(C'\fR interaction
products). Aliased columns are reported as \f(CW\*(C`NaN\*(C'\fR, which \f(CW\*(C`predict\*(C'\fR drops.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fR\f(CB\*(C`fitted.values\*(C'\fR\fB\fR ŌĆö \f(CW\*(C`Xb\*(C'\fR over the non\-aliased columns, keyed by surviving row
name. Computed from a snapshot of the design (\f(CW\*(C`Dsav\*(C'\fR) taken before the QR
overwrites \f(CW\*(C`X_mat\*(C'\fR. Costs one transient copy of the design matrix; negligible for
typical ANOVA where the column count is small.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fR\f(CB\*(C`xlevels\*(C'\fR\fB\fR ŌĆö sorted level list per factor, index 0 = reference, aligned with
the contrast coding used to build the dummies.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fR\f(CB\*(C`family\*(C'\fR\fB\fR ŌĆö \f(CW"gaussian"\fR.
.PP
Cleanup\-path correctness
.IX Subsection "Cleanup-path correctness"
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`xlevels_hv\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`Dsav\*(C'\fR, and \f(CW\*(C`surv_names\*(C'\fR are freed on both the "0 degrees of
freedom" croak and the normal exit. The interaction\-main\-effects croak in
PHASE 3 also frees \f(CW\*(C`xlevels_hv\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Known limitations (unchanged)
.IX Subsection "Known limitations (unchanged)"
.IP \(bu 4
The intercept\-stripping string surgery (\f(CW\-1\fR, \f(CW+0\fR, \f(CW+1\fR, ...) operates on the
whole RHS and can still mangle \f(CWI(x\-1)\fR\-style transforms; treat \f(CWI()\fR with
arithmetic constants carefully.
.IP \(bu 4
Top\-level keys \f(CW\*(C`coefficients\*(C'\fR / \f(CW\*(C`fitted.values\*(C'\fR / \f(CW\*(C`xlevels\*(C'\fR / \f(CW\*(C`family\*(C'\fR /
\&\f(CW\*(C`group_stats\*(C'\fR share the return hash with the ANOVA rows; a predictor literally
named one of those would collide.
.PP
\fR\f(CI\*(C`predict\*(C'\fR\fI\fR
.IX Subsection "predict"
.PP
New: factor\-bearing interaction terms
.IX Subsection "New: factor-bearing interaction terms"
.PP
Previously, interaction coefficients such as \f(CW\*(C`GroupB:Sexmale\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`GroupB:x\*(C'\fR fell
through to the continuous \f(CW\*(C`evaluate_term\*(C'\fR path and died on a nonexistent column.
They are now handled directly:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fR\f(CB\*(C`dummy_hv\*(C'\fR\fB\fR stores each dummy\*(Aqs factor base index (an \f(CW\*(C`IV\*(C'\fR) instead of
\&\f(CW&PL_sv_yes\fR, so a dummy name maps back to its \f(CW\*(C`(base, level)\*(C'\fR in O(1)
(\f(CW\*(C`level == name + strlen(base)\*(C'\fR). \f(CW\*(C`hv_exists\*(C'\fR lookups are unaffected.
.IP \(bu 4
During coefficient caching, any \f(CW\*(C`:\*(C'\fR term with at least one factor\-dummy component
is routed to a separate list (\f(CW\*(C`icopy\*(C'\fR / \f(CW\*(C`ibeta\*(C'\fR); pure\-continuous interactions
(e.g. \f(CW\*(C`x:z\*(C'\fR) stay on the existing \f(CW\*(C`evaluate_term\*(C'\fR path, so prior behavior is
preserved.
.IP \(bu 4
Each routed term is parsed once into flat component arrays. Factor components
store a base index and level pointer; continuous components store the term string
and get the same up\-front column\-existence validation as main terms.
.IP \(bu 4
Per row, each factor\*(Aqs raw level is read once into \f(CW\*(C`raw_lv[]\*(C'\fR and reused by both
main effects and interactions (no duplicate \f(CW\*(C`get_data_string_alloc\*(C'\fR). An
interaction\*(Aqs value is the product of its components: a factor component
contributes \f(CW1.0\fR iff the row\*(Aqs level matches the dummy\*(Aqs level (reference levels
give \f(CW0\fR), continuous components go through \f(CW\*(C`evaluate_term\*(C'\fR.
.PP
This covers factor├Śfactor, factor├Ścontinuous, continuous├Ścontinuous, and n\-way
combinations.
.PP
Other
.IX Subsection "Other"
.IP \(bu 4
HoH row count uses \f(CW\*(C`HvUSEDKEYS\*(C'\fR (already present).
.IP \(bu 4
The unseen\-factor\-level croak now frees every level string already read for the
current row, not just the current one.
.PP
\fITests\fR
.IX Subsection "Tests"
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fR\f(CB\*(C`aov.t\*(C'\fR\fB\fR ŌĆö one\-way ANOVA against hand\-computed values (Df / Sum Sq / Mean Sq /
F / decomposition); identical results across HoA / HoH / AoH / stacked input;
simple regression; \f(CW\*(C`.\*(C'\fR expansion; intercept removal (\f(CW\-1\fR); two\-way with
interaction (Type I SS on a balanced design); NaN listwise deletion; all croak
paths; leak checks.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fR\f(CB\*(C`predict.t\*(C'\fR\fB\fR ŌĆö \f(CW\*(C`predict(training) == fitted.values\*(C'\fR round\-trips for one\-way,
regression, factor├Śfactor, factor├Ścontinuous, and continuous├Ścontinuous models;
explicit predicted values; agreement across HoA / AoH / HoH / flat newdata;
no\-newdata path; binomial \f(CW\*(C`link\*(C'\fR vs \f(CW\*(C`response\*(C'\fR; gaussian identity link; all croak
paths; leak checks.
.PP
Leak tests use \f(CW\*(C`no_leaks_ok\*(C'\fR guarded by \f(CW\*(C`unless $INC{\*(AqDevel/Cover.pm\*(Aq}\*(C'\fR and skipped
when \f(CW\*(C`Test::LeakTrace\*(C'\fR is absent.
.PP
Assumptions worth confirming
.IX Subsection "Assumptions worth confirming"
.IP \(bu 4
The NaN\-deletion test relies on \f(CW\*(C`evaluate_term\*(C'\fR returning \f(CW\*(C`NaN\*(C'\fR for a non\-finite
response value (an \f(CW\*(C`Inf \- Inf\*(C'\fR NaN is fed in deterministically).
.IP \(bu 4
The continuous├Ścontinuous round\-trip relies on \f(CWevaluate_term("x:z")\fR yielding
\&\f(CW\*(C`x * z\*(C'\fR ŌĆö the same assumption the pre\-existing \f(CW\*(C`predict\*(C'\fR continuous\-interaction
path already made. If that path was untested, this round\-trip now exercises it.
.PP
\fR\f(CI\*(C`view\*(C'\fR\fI\fR
.IX Subsection "view"
.PP
now returns colored output; fixed bug with incorrect widths; undefined values show as \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR rather than \f(CW\*(C`NA\*(C'\fR, as in Data::Printer
.PP
\fR\f(CI\*(C`csort\*(C'\fR\fI\fR
.IX Subsection "csort"
.PP
now accepts Hash of Hashes; addition of \f(CW\*(C`restrict\*(C'\fR which should decrease calculation time
.PP
\fIfilter\fR
.IX Subsection "filter"
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fBAdded hash\-of\-hashes (HoH) input.\fR In addition to AoH and HoA, \f(CW\*(C`filter\*(C'\fR now accepts an HoH (\f(CW\*(C`{ key => { col => val, ... }, ... }\*(C'\fR); each inner hash is one row, and matching keys are preserved by default (HoH \-> HoH).
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fBAdded \fR\f(CB\*(C`output.type\*(C'\fR\fB.\fR \f(CW\*(C`filter($df, $pred, \*(Aqoutput.type\*(Aq => \*(Aqaoh\*(Aq|\*(Aqhoa\*(Aq)\*(C'\fR selects the returned shape (aliases \f(CW\*(C`out\*(C'\fR / \f(CW\*(C`output_type\*(C'\fR; a bare positional type also works). When omitted, the input shape is preserved. \f(CW\*(C`hoh\*(C'\fR is not a selectable output, since it would require choosing a key column.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fR\f(CBcol()\fR\fB reworked, not removed.\fR Both predicate forms are kept: \f(CW\*(C`col(\*(Aqage\*(Aq) >= 18\*(C'\fR still works and is the concise/composable option, while a coderef covers everything else. Internally \f(CWcol()\fR is now \fBpure Perl\fR ŌĆö an overloaded class that builds a per\-row closure ŌĆö and \f(CW\*(C`filter\*(C'\fR unwraps that closure so \f(CWcol()\fR and a coderef share one evaluation path. The previous standalone XS predicate evaluator (\f(CW\*(C`filt_eval\*(C'\fR/\f(CW\*(C`filt_ctx\*(C'\fR) is gone; delete it if your tree still has it. One consequence: a \f(CWcol()\fR comparison now costs the same per row as the equivalent coderef (a Perl call), rather than being evaluated in C.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\fBUnchanged guarantees:\fR the input frame is never modified; \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR (and, for numeric ops, non\-numeric) cells never match a \f(CWcol()\fR comparison; AoH/HoH rows are shared rather than copied where possible; keep\-all/keep\-none shapes are well defined per output type; Perl 5.10 compatibility is retained. A latent \f(CWSvTRUE(POPs)\fR double\-evaluation in the per\-row call helper (which crashed on perls where \f(CW\*(C`SvTRUE\*(C'\fR is a multi\-eval macro) was fixed along the way.
.PP
\fIread_table\fR
.IX Subsection "read_table"
.PP
Added an opt\-in \f(CW\*(C`auto.row.names\*(C'\fR argument so \f(CW\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fR can read the file R
produces by default from \f(CW\*(C`write.table(x, sep="\et")\*(C'\fR.
.PP
The problem
.IX Subsection "The problem"
.PP
R\*(Aqs \f(CW\*(C`write.table\*(C'\fR defaults to \f(CW\*(C`row.names=TRUE, col.names=TRUE\*(C'\fR, which writes the
row\-names column in every data row but emits \fBno header label for it\fR. So a
frame with N columns comes out as N header fields over N+1 data fields ŌĆö e.g.
\&\f(CW\*(C`mtcars\*(C'\fR gives 11 headers but 12\-field rows. By default \f(CW\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fR (correctly)
rejects that as ragged:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& Alignment error on mtcars.tsv data row 1 (12 fields vs 11 headers).
.Ve
.PP
The change
.IX Subsection "The change"
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`auto.row.names\*(C'\fR turns on R\*(Aqs own \f(CW\*(C`read.table\*(C'\fR rule: \fBwhen, and only when, the
header is exactly one field short of the data rows, treat the first field of
each row as an (unlabelled) row\-names column.\fR
.PP
.Vb 2
\& # default: the leading column is named \*(Aqrow_name\*(Aq
\& my $df = read_table(\*(Aqmtcars.tsv\*(Aq, \*(Aqauto.row.names\*(Aq => 1);
\& 
\& # or give it a name
\& my $df = read_table(\*(Aqmtcars.tsv\*(Aq, \*(Aqauto.row.names\*(Aq => \*(Aqmodel\*(Aq);
.Ve
.PP
The synthesized column behaves like any other first column: it appears in \f(CW\*(C`aoh\*(C'\fR
and \f(CW\*(C`hoa\*(C'\fR output, and for \f(CW\*(C`hoh\*(C'\fR it becomes the default key (so rows are keyed by
the model name). This also lines up with the existing handling of R\*(Aqs
\&\f(CW\*(C`col.names=NA\*(C'\fR output (a blank leading header), which still produces a
\&\f(CW\*(C`row_name\*(C'\fR column with no flag needed.
.PP
What did not change
.IX Subsection "What did not change"
.PP
The strict alignment check is still the default. Without \f(CW\*(C`auto.row.names\*(C'\fR the
lopsided file still croaks, and even with it, a row that is off by anything
other than exactly one field still croaks ŌĆö so the corruption guard only relaxes
for the one case R itself treats specially.
.PP
Tested in \f(CW\*(C`t/read_table.2.t\*(C'\fR (16 assertions, Perl 5.10.1 and 5.38): aoh / hoa /
hoh output, custom column name, the already\-aligned file (flag is a no\-op), the
\&\f(CW\*(C`col.names=NA\*(C'\fR path, and the strict / ragged croak paths.
.PP
additional bugfix
.IX Subsection "additional bugfix"
.PP
.Vb 5
\& # This is a comment
\& id,name,val
\& 1,Alice,10.5
\& 2,Bob,
\& 3,Charlie,15.2
.Ve
.PP
would not be read correctly using \f(CW\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fR, but now is read correctly
.PP
